content:
Insurance Product Modeling includes two levels of inheritance: child spec inheritance and product class inheritance. 

Inheritance allows for changes to be made at any time, which are then inherited by every product model using the child spec or product class without individual updates being required.

Child Spec Inheritance:

* All options and configurations on each attribute
* Attribute rules
* Attribute value rules

When a change is made to one of these parts of an original child spec, those changes are inherited by all instances of the child spec attached to root product specs.

Types of child specs that this inheritance model applies to: 
Coverage spec 
Insured Item spec 
Insured Party spec 
Rating Fact spec 

You can override any attribute, attribute configuration, or rule on an instance of a child spec attached to a root product spec.

Product Class Inheritance:

* Rating Procedure Name
* Rating Procedure Type
* Coverages
* Insured Item
* Insured Party
* Rating Facts
* Product Rules

When creating product models based on a product class, additions and changes can be made to items not inherited from the product class, such as taxes & fees, new attributes at the root product level, coverages, insured items, and product rules.

However, modifications or deletions cannot be made to items inherited from product specs, including:

* Coverages
* Insured items and insured parties
* Attributes on child specs or product
* Product rules
title: Understanding Insurance Product Inheritance
